1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,500
That amazing deal might be a
fake website. Here's how to check.

2
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Every time you shop online,
start with this quick check.

3
00:00:06,500 --> 00:00:09,500
Look at the top of your browser
at the website address.

4
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:13,000
You should see a padlock icon
and the address starts with https.

5
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:16,000
No padlock? Leave immediately.
Don't enter any details.

6
00:00:16,500 --> 00:00:19,500
Second — check the website name
very carefully.

7
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:23,500
Scammers make sites like
"amazon-deals.net" that look real.

8
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,000
The real Amazon is just
amazon.com. Nothing extra.

9
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:30,500
Third — the prices. If
everything is 70-80% off —

10
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,000
with no explanation,
the site is probably fake.

11
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:37,500
Check the payment options.
Real stores take credit cards.

12
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,000
If a site only takes gift cards
or bank transfers — leave.

13
00:00:41,500 --> 00:00:44,500
Those methods have no
consumer protection.

14
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,500
When you do shop online,
use a credit card if you have one.

15
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Credit cards give you the
strongest protection of all.

16
00:00:52,500 --> 00:00:56,000
If something goes wrong, your
card company must refund you.

17
00:00:56,500 --> 00:01:00,000
If a purchase goes wrong,
contact the seller first.

18
00:01:00,500 --> 00:01:03,500
Give them 5 days. No response?
Open a dispute through the platform.

19
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Check the padlock, read the address,
and always pay by card.

20
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:10,500
Full guide at TekSure.com.
